node.title: 36-million-year-old fossil of "sea monster" found in desert
node.description: The "Ocucaje Predator" was about 55 feet long and used its massive, powerful teeth to feed on tuna and sharks.

node.title: House passes bill banning race-based hair discrimination
node.description: The legislation lists among hairstyles it would protect, those "in which hair is tightly coiled or tightly curled, locs, cornrows, twists, braids, Bantu knots and Afros."

node.title: Cosmonauts launched to space station as NASA chief touts cooperation with Russia
node.description: The launch clears the way for an American astronaut to return to Earth on March 30 aboard another Russian spacecraft.

node.title: McCarthy says Madison Cawthorn is "wrong" about Zelenskyy
node.description: The North Carolina Republican called the Ukrainian president a "thug" and said the Ukrainian government is "incredibly evil."

node.title: Book excerpt: "Every Good Boy Does Fine" by Jeremy Denk
node.description: In his new memoir the acclaimed classical pianist writes of the life of a musician, and offers a tribute to those who influenced him: music teachers, conductors – and his father.

node.title: Watchdog reports unsanitary conditions and staff shortages at ICE facility
node.description: The U.S. Department of Homeland Security Office of Inspector General issued the rare recommendation in a report about the Torrance County Detention Facility.

node.title: DNA identified in search for 17-year-old girl missing since 2004
node.description: Brianna Maitland was last seen on the evening of March 19, 2004, when she left work at the Black Lantern Inn.

node.title: Cardona on why "fixing a broken" student loan system is a priority
node.description: Americans owe more than $1.7 trillion in student loan debt in the United States.

node.title: Biden and Xi set to clash over Putin's war in Ukraine
node.description: US President Joe Biden is expected to tell Chinese President Xi Jinping on Friday that Beijing will pay a price if it supports Russia's military operations in Ukraine

node.title: Verstappen and Hamilton rivalry set to reignite
node.description: Lewis Hamilton and Max Verstappen lead Formula One into a new era in Bahrain this weekend as the sport seeks to move on from one of its most controversial seasons.

node.title: London cop convicted of rape and murder faces 4 new charges
node.description: The offenses allegedly took place just before former police officer Wayne Couzens killed Sarah Everard on March 3 in a case that sparked nationwide protests.

node.title: Texas wildfires prompt hundreds of evacuations
node.description: The fires have burned about 71 square miles, according to Texas A&M Forest Service​, with only 4% containment.

node.title: "Lifelong friends" of Ketanji Brown Jackson show their support
node.description: If confirmed, Judge Jackson would also be the first former public defender on the high court.

node.title: FBI informant "Big Dan" testifies about Gov. Whitmer kidnap plot
node.description: "We want her flex-cuffed on a table while we all pose and get our pictures taken," one defendant said of Whitmer.

node.title: Freckle-faced killer Eric Smith, now 42, freed on parole, says he's engaged
node.description: Smith was 13 when he murdered a child in 1993. After 28 years behind bars, he has a new life and says he's a changed man.

node.title: New York cop pleads guilty to sexually abusing woman he threatened with arrest
node.description: Michael Agovino told a woman he was investigating her, and threatened her with arrest, before sexually abusing her on multiple occasions

node.title: North Carolina investigating whether Meadows committed voter fraud
node.description: State authorities are investigating whether Meadows illegally used a North Carolina address where he did not reside in order to vote in 2020.

node.title: Inside a Ukraine town's bloody David vs. Goliath battle to repel Russia
node.description: Ukraine's outgunned defenders know if Russian troops get past Voznesensk, they will march on to Odesa. "This is where we stopped them," the town's mayor tells CBS News.

node.title: This week on "Sunday Morning" (March 20)
node.description: A look at the features for this week's broadcast of the #1 Sunday morning news program

node.title: Florida bus driver hailed for "her quick actions" as gunman kills 2
node.description: The bus driver barreled into the parking lot of the Fort Lauderdale police headquarters after a gunman opened fire on the bus.

node.title: Most medical debt will be dropped from credit reports
node.description: The top three credit bureaus said they'll remove about 70% of medical debt their reports starting this summer.

node.title: Volkswagen recalls more than 246,000 SUVs in North America
node.description: Automaker says faulty wiring can result in unexpected braking, sometimes while vehicles are sitting in traffic.

node.title: Putin calls opponents "scum and traitors," signaling new repression
node.description: Putin's ominous speech likened opponents to "gnats" who try to weaken the country at the behest of the West.

node.title: Bridge tender arrested in death of woman who fell when it opened
node.description: Artissua Paulk, 43, was charged with one count of manslaughter by culpable negligence.

node.title: Biden speaking with China's Xi Jinping
node.description: White House press secretary Jen Psaki said Russia's war against Ukraine is among the issues the two will discuss.

node.title: Russia hits Lviv for 1st time as aerial assault on Ukraine intensifies
node.description: Putin's artillery reportedly hit a facility for repairing planes in Lviv, near Ukraine's western border with Poland, as Kyiv and other big cities face a ceaseless onslaught.

node.title: Son of man on death row makes plea to Formula One star Lewis Hamilton
node.description: Ahead of the season-opening F1 race in Bahrain, the boy is hopeful that the British driver can help save his father's life.

node.title: Taliban detains journalists over report on censoring of TV shows
node.description: The arrests were met with international outcry, including calls for the Taliban to stop harassing local journalists and stifling free expression through threats, arrests and intimidation.

node.title: Underwater expedition goes "where no other human being had been before"
node.description: The Atacama Trench lies in an area that has produced many earthquakes and tsunamis.

node.title: Finland named world's happiest country for fifth straight year
node.description: Afghanistan is at the bottom of the list. The U.S. rose three spots, to 16th. The rankings are based on people's own assessment of their happiness, as well as economic and social data.
